MissionCommands.Message: Welcome to the maneuvering lesson! Gemini has the capability to alter its current orbital trajectory. To do this, the OAMS thrusters are used to translate the craft in any direction.

Executing burns is a semi-manual process. The on-board computer (OBC) will first need to be configured with the burn vector, known as delta-V, or delta-velocity, the change you wish to append to the current velocity.
In addition, the computer will need to know when the change in velocity will take place.
All OAMS/OBC burns are done in the CATCH UP module, a program in the OBC specially designed to execute burns.
Set the computer mode to CATCH UP.

The AUX TAPE system will now be used to load the CATCH UP module into the OBC memory. This takes 10 minutes, after which the AUX TAPE RUN light will extinguish. Use TIMESCALE until the loading is complete, and press ROGER when ready.
Burns can be set up by either GROUND through DCS (mission) or through a radio request using the MISSION TOOLs.
Press [C] to toggle the bubble-functions and click on the MISSION TOOLS bubble. This will open a new view where you can perform various actions related to the mission, and request burns.

Select GROUND->REQUEST BURNS from the list. Do not select any of them yet. Once you do, you will receive a couple of messages from GROUND containing burn information and a PAD containing data about the burn.

Ok, go ahead and press REQUEST PE CIRCULARIZATION BURN and close the MISSION TOOLS window. This will request GROUND to calculate a burn that will circulate your orbit at Perigee, the lowest point in your current orbit. Press ROGER on both messages. We will look at the data shortly.
Great, let's use the TRANSCRIPT in the MISSION PAD to review the data. Open the MISSION PAD and press the TRANSCRIPT tab, then find the two messages containing the burn data.

The first message is a summary of the burn that has been uplinked through DCS. Each time you receive a DCS message (data uplinked from GROUND), the DCS light will illuminate. Press the DCS button to reset the light.
The next message is the PAD data, Preliminary Advisory Data, and is basically all the information you will need related to a burn.
Does the message seem intimidating? This message has a specific format, and once you understand it, it will be easy to read.
To understand the message, let's open the PAD form for a CATCH UP BURN MANEUVER. Once again, open the MISSION TOOLS window again, then press DATA FORMS->CATCH UP MANEUVER PAD.
The CATCH UP MANEUVER PAD is used to write down the data in the PAD you received from GROUND. Close the MISSION TOOLs window.

You can resize the PAD window and move it around on the screen. To start drawing in it, press the brush-icon on the top/right bar of the PAD window. This will disable the resizing tool, but enable drawing. You can toggle this as you like.

Using the left mouse button you can draw on the sheet. In addition, various tools are available in the tool bar, including "stamps" for numerics and +/-, along with a shortcut for the PEN and ERASER tool. You can use the mouse scroll wheel to quickly select these.
Try this out now and get familiar with how the drawing tools work.
Now, using the tools we will type in the data from the PAD. NOTE: This can also be done on paper or on a pad outside the sim instead.

The first part of the PAD is entered into the two rows of the BURN section. This section describes the purpose of the burn and how it will be executed. Type in Pe CIRC in the first row, and OAMS/OBC in the 2nd row.

Next we have the GETI (ground elapsed time of ignition) section, which also contains two rows. The numbers after the OAMS/OBC entry in the PAD message from GROUND are the first part of the ignition timestamp (mission time), and are read in a special format.

If the number is 00111, this tells you that the ignition should happen at 001 hours and 11 minutes into the mission. The format of the number is HHHMM, and can be seen on the PAD. Type this into the sheet.

The next number is also part of the time of ignition and specifies the seconds and milliseconds at ignition. It also has 5 digits, where the first digit is always a zero, the next two digits are seconds and the last two are hundreds and tens of milliseconds. Type it into the sheet.
If the number was 02388, you can read it as 23.88 seconds. The two GETI fields tell you the exact time of ignition. The OBC will need to know this data.
The next section is the ΔV in Local Vertical at the time of ignition (GETI that you just typed down). The X-axis is forward/backwards, the Y-axis is Left/Right and the Z-axis is Up/Down.

Most burns will only contain data on the X-axis. Since this is a Pe-circulation burn, the ΔX is negative (retrograde direction). This is indicated with a "9" as the first digit, since the OBC does not have + or - buttons.
Type this into the PAD. On the form you will notice a decimal between the 4th and 5th digits. So the format is XXXX.X, where the first X can be a 9 (negative value) or a 0 (positive value).

So if the ΔX value reads 90657, it means -65.7 ft/s in the X-axis, a retrograde burn. If it would be an Ap-circulation burn, it would be positive, so 00657, +65.7 ft/s. Type the data from your own transcript into the sheet.
The BT row is the burn time in seconds. Type this into the sheet.
The entire ATT section can be skipped for now, but it contains the direction of the burn vector with respect to your current inertial platform.

The next two entries in the PAD are Ha and Hp, the predicted altitudes of the resulting orbit after the burn is executed. The numbers are specified in nautical miles (nmi) altitude above the surface of Earth. Ha corresponds to your new Ap, and Hp will be your new Pe.
And that's it for the basics of the PAD. Any time you receive a PAD, just follow the order of the data in the message and type them down in the correct sheet in the same order.
Once you have the PAD, the data can be inserted into the OBC. This is done automatically using DCS uplink from ground, but you should always verify the data you get.
Look at the right side of the PAD next to the two GETI lines. You will see the numbers 01 and 02. These are the core addresses where the data should be inserted. Let's check the first core register.
On the OBC MDU, press 0 and 1. The ADDRESS of the MDU should now read 01. Then press READ OUT. Verify that this data matches the PAD.
If its not, simply type in the 5 digits and press ENTER. But the data should be correct due to DCS uplink.
You might have noticed that all of the values that should be inserted into the OBC are already in the correct format in the PAD. All are 5 digits, with 0 or 9 for positive and negative values.
This makes it easy to program a planned burn into the computer.
Let's verify the next GETI data point. Hit CLEAR on the MDU and then key 0, 2, READ OUT. The data should match the PAD. If it doesn't, key in the correct 5 digits and hit ENTER.
Then check core 25. Key 2, 5, READ OUT and verify the ΔX value from the PAD matches the data in the MDU. Type it in if it does not match.
Do the same for core 26 (ΔY) and core 27 (ΔZ).
The OBC is now configured for the burn. You can close the CATCH UP MANEUVER PAD if you wish; you can always bring it back up from the MISSION TOOLS menu.
Once we have inserted the burn data into the OBC, the burn can be calculated by pressing START.
The OBC will now calculate the burn and display the burn vector on the IVIs. To cross check, key 8, 4, READ OUT on the MDU. This will show you the countdown to the burn in minutes and seconds.
Keep in mind that the MDIU is a mechanical device which can take up to three and a half seconds to show a value. This means that there is a slight offset in the time to burn when you see the data.
The first 3 digits represent total minutes to burn, and the last two digits are in seconds, so MMM:SS is the format. If it shows 04855, it means that 48 minutes and 55 seconds remain until the burn.

Set the EVENT TIMER mode to stop (so it does not count), configure it to 10:00 (minutes:seconds), and the counting direction to DOWN. You can use Core 84 as a reference, but configure the Event Timer using the GETI from the PAD.

Monitor the MISSION TIMER in the center panel. The burn should happen when it is equal to GETI from the PAD. At 10 minutes left to ignition, start the event timer to make it easy to see when ignition should happen.
The COMP light will also extinguish 2 minutes before the burn, and illuminate again when you should start the burn. So when the light goes out, prepare to burn, and when it goes back on, execute.
Enable OAMS and try BEF, SEF and manual controls and pay attention to the IVIs.
The IVIs display the burn vector that should happen at GETI relative to your local body axis. As you change your attitude, the IVIs will update and show you what directions to burn to zero the IVIs.
This means that since the OAMS translation can be done in any direction, your spacecraft can perform the ΔV burn in any attitude.
That said, it is far easier to perform the burn if the majority if it happens in one axis. Typically you want to be in BEF or SEF during the burn.
If the burn is a ΔX burn (prograde or retrograde) like this, most of the ΔV can be done using the fwd/aft thrusters.

When you see the COMP light turn back on AND when the countdown reaches the ignition time, simply zero the IVIs and the burn will complete. Timing is key, and duration is important (so execute the entire burn as fast as you can).
Good luck! Get into a circular orbit as planned.
Great job! Now hit the RESET button on the computer to finalize the burn procedures.
It is important to not let the computer RUN/COMPUTE an old burn, or the IVIs will show misleading numbers.
All of the burn procedures can be found in the MISSION PAD->CIRCULARIZE ORBIT and RENDEZVOUS checklists.
Great job. No matter what OAMS/OBC burn you will execute, it is done with these procedures. This concludes this lesson.

Title: Tutorial 9 - Maneuvering & OAMS Burns
Description: In this lesson you will learn how to request a burn and how to read the PAD (Preliminary Advisory Data), a data format that contains all information related to a burn. The PAD is designed so that it will be easier to insert the data into the OBC. We will then use the PAD to set up for a burn and execute it.
